{{Expand German|Ba'ja|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox historic site | name =Ba'ja | image = Ba'ja 01.jpg | caption = Ba'ja, Excavation Area B | location = [[Jordan]] | locmapin = Jordan | coordinates = {{coord|30|24|49|N|35|27|41|E|display=inline}} | map_caption = Location of Ba'ja in [[Jordan]] }} [[file:Ba'ja 02.jpg|thumb|Areas B, E and TU 2]] [[file:Ba'ja 08.jpg|thumb|Walls in Area TU2]] '''Ba'ja''' ({{lang-ar|بعجة}}) is a [[Neolithic]] village {{convert|14|km|mi}} north of [[Petra]], [[Jordan]]. Like the nearby site of [[Basta (Jordan)|Basta]], the settlement was built in c. {{dts|-7000}}, during the PPNB ([[Pre-Pottery Neolithic B]]) period. Ba'ja lies at an altitude of around {{convert|1160|m|ft}}, and is only accessible with a climbing route through a narrow, steep canyon. <ref>[http://www.bai-wuppertal.de/baja-i-jordanien Ba'ja I Grabungsergebnisse], [[Biblisch-Archäologisches Institut Wuppertal|BAI Wuppertal]]</ref>
Near the entrance to the site is Ba'ja I, an Islamic settlement with 2-3 layers of an older [[Nabataean]] settlement.
