{{for|the American diplomat|Eric G. John}}
'''Eric John''' (1922–2000) was a reader in history at the [[University of Manchester]] and a specialist in [[Anglo-Saxon history]]. He was described by [[James Campbell (historian)|James Campbell]] as "one of the most distinguished and provocative of Anglo-Saxonists"<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7ju8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA214&lpg=PA214&dq=eric+john+university+of+manchester&source=bl&ots=gvmP74PbO-&sig=HkxIVjYWG9Wfztxzwq_lfBa1OPg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CFAQ6AEwCGoVChMI8YWd45j3xgIVClUUCh2KmAKr#v=onepage&q=eric%20john%20university%20of%20manchester&f=false Foreword by James Campbell to John's Reassessing Anglo-Saxon England (1996)]</ref><ref>[http://www.alc.manchester.ac.uk/subjects/history/research/centres/former-centres/mancass/ Manchester Centre for Anglo-Saxon Studies (MANCASS)]</ref> D. H. Farmer described his studies of the [[English Benedictine Reform]], mainly in pages 154-264 of ''Orbis Britanniae'', as "both stimulating and provocative; even those who cannot assent to all his conclusions recognise that he has brought a new dimension to the study of the reform".<ref>{{cite book|editor-first= David|editor-last= Parsons |first=David Hugh |last=Farmer|chapter=The Progress of the Monastic Revival|page=209, n. 1|title=Tenth-Century Studies: Essays in Commemoration of the Millennium of the Council of Winchester and the Regularis Concordia |authorlink= |publisher= Phillimore|location = Chichester, UK |year=1975 |edition= |isbn= 0 85033 179 X }}</ref>

His books included:
*{{cite book|title= The king and the monks in the tenth-century Reformation|publisher= John Rylands Library|location=Manchester, UK |year= 1959 |oclc=35146827 }}
*{{cite book|title= Land tenure in early England; a discussion of some problems|publisher= Leicester University Press|location=Leicester, UK |year= 1960 |oclc=2311824 }}
*{{cite book|title=Orbis Britanniae|publisher=Leicester University Press|location=Leicester, UK|year=1966|oclc=398831}}
*{{cite book|title= Reassessing Anglo-Saxon England|publisher= Manchester University Press|location =Manchester, UK  |year= 1996 |isbn= 0 7190 5053 7}}

He also contributed chapters on the later Anglo-Saxon period in ''The Anglo-Saxons'' (1982), edited by James Campbell; and "The Social and Political Problems of the Early English Church" in ''Anglo-Saxon History: Basic Readings'' (2000) edited by David Pelteret.

''Edward the Elder 899-924'' (2001) was dedicated as a memorial to the life and work of Eric John.<ref>{{cite book|editors= N. J. Higham & D. H. Hill |title= Edward the Elder 899–924|publisher= Routledge|page=v|isbn=0-415-21497-1}}</ref>

