{{italic title}}
[[File:Marie Laurent-Erinnyes-01.jpg|thumb|]]
'''''Les Érinnyes''''' (The [[Erinyes]]) is a [[French language]] [[verse drama]] written by [[Leconte de Lisle]] and premièred at the [[Théâtre de l'Odéon]] in 1873. It is in the style of a [[Greek tragedy]], in two [[Act (drama)|act]]s: ''Klytaimnestra'' ([[Clytemnestra]]) and ''Orestès'' ([[Orestes]]). It was an adaptation of the first two parts of [[Aeschylus]]' ''[[Oresteia]]'' (''Agamemnon'' and ''Libation Bearers'').<ref name="MacintoshMichelakis2005">{{cite book|last1=Macintosh|first1=Fiona|last2=Michelakis|first2=Pantelis|last3=Hall|first3=Edith|author4=Oliver Taplin|title=Agamemnon in Performance 458 BC to AD 2004|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R7p3aqVDOiYC&pg=PR165|accessdate=5 July 2012|date=2005-12-08|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780191608360|pages=clxv–clxvi}}</ref>  The text was printed in de Lisle's collection ''Poèmes Tragiques''.

==Massenet's music==
[[Félix Duquesnel|Félix-Henri Duquesnel]] produced a [[Revival (theatre)|revival]] of the play in 1876 at the Théâtre du [[Gaité]].<ref name="Coquis1965">{{cite book|last=Coquis|first=André|title=Jules Massenet: l'homme et son oeuvre|year=1965|publisher=Éditions Seghers|language=French|page=22}}</ref> He commissioned his friend [[Jules Massenet]] to write an [[overture]], [[intermezzo]], and [[incidental music]] (respectively a ''Prélude'', ''Entr'acte'', and two ''Mélodrames'').<ref name="Coquis1965"/> The music ([[Opus number]] 10) was conducted at the première by [[Édouard Colonne]]. It was an early boost to Massenet's career. He wrote in his memoirs:<ref>{{cite book |last=Massenet  |first=Jules |others=translator H. Villiers Barnett |title=My Recollections |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/36728/36728-h/36728-h.htm#CHAPTER_IX |year=1919 |publisher=Small, Maynard |location=Boston |chapter=IX: The Days After the War}}</ref>
:Dusquesnel placed forty musicians at my disposal, which, under the circumstances, was a considerable expense and a great favor. Instead of writing a score for the regular orchestra—which would have produced only a paltry effect—I had the idea of having a quartet of thirty-six stringed instruments corresponding to a large orchestra. Then I added three [[trombone]]s to represent the three Erinnyes: [[Tisiphone]], [[Alecto]] and [[Megere]], and a pair of [[kettle-drum]]s. So I had my forty.

{{anchor|Élégie}}
The well known "Invocation'" accompanies Electra's pouring of libations on the [[tomb of Agamemnon]] in act 2.   It was published separately as the ''[[Elegy|Élégie]]'' for cello and orchestra (Op.10, no.5) as well as the song "O doux printemps d'autrefois" and still often performed and recorded. Massenet originally wrote it as part of a competition to score the opera ''La coupe du roi de Thulé'', with libretto by [[Louis Gallet]] and [[Édouard Blau]].<ref name="Schneider1926">{{cite book|last=Schneider|first=Louis|title=Massenet (1842-1912)|year=1926|publisher=Bibliothèque-Charpentier|language=French|page=265}}</ref> Massenet's entry came second to that of [[Eugène Diaz]].<ref name="Schneider1926"/>

