{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}} A '''normal play''' '''convention''' in a game is the method of determining the winner that is generally regarded as standard. For example: *Preventing the other player from being able to move *Being the first player to achieve a target *Holding the highest value hand *Taking the most [[Trick-taking game|card tricks]]
In [[combinatorial game theory]], the normal play convention of an [[impartial game]] is that the last player able to move is the winner.
By contrast "[[misère game]]s" involve upsetting the convention and declaring a winner the individual who would normally be considered the loser.
[[Category:Gaming]]
{{DEFAULTSORT:Normal Play Convention}}
{{Game-stub}}

{{refimprove|date=April 2013}}

The '''Quimbaya artifacts''' are several dozen golden objects, found in [[Colombia]], made by the [[Quimbaya civilization]] culture, dated around 1000 CE, a few of which (the so-called '''Quimbaya airplanes''') are supposed by [[ancient astronaut]]s theorists to represent modern airplanes, and therefore to be [[out-of-place artifact]]s. The whole of the figurines, measuring 2 to 3 inches (5 to 7.5&nbsp;cm) each, are described in mainstream archaeology as depicting birds, lizards, amphibians and insects common in that region and period, some of them highly stylized, as in the [[Gold Museum, Bogotá]].

In 1994, Germans Peter Belting and Conrad Lubbers created simplified radio-controlled scale models of these objects and showed that their models, which lack some convoluted features present in the real figurines, could fly.<ref>{{cite book |last=Thomas |first=Robert Steven |title=Intelligent Intervention |year=2011 |publisher=Dog Ear Publishing |location=USA |isbn=978-1-4575-0778-6 |pages=74–77 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f4-xgGKtIUEC&pg=PA76&dq=quimbaya+artefacts+plane&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0bUzUcDuLYbDyQGsx4DoAg&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=quimbaya%20artefacts%20plane&f=false}}</ref>

